<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Decides to Expand Mission in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday decided to authorize "the provisional expansion" of the
U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNMOSIL).
</P>
<P>
The decision was contained in a resolution unanimously adopted
by the 15 Council members. As of July 29, there were 48 military
observers in Sierra Leone, they are from such countries as China,
Bangladesh, India, Pakistan, Russia, the United Kingdom and
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "authorizes the provisional expansion of
UNMOSIL to up to 210 military observers along with the necessary
equipment and administrative and medical support to perform the
tasks" to promote peace in the West African country, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also welcomed the July 7 signing of the Peace
Agreement between the Government of Sierra Leone and the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) in Lome, capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The resolution commended the Sierra Leonean Government and
the West African peacekeepers for their contribution to
advancing the peace process in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the resolution stressed "the importance of the
safety, security and freedom of movement of United Nations and
associated personnel."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council encouraged the ongoing consultations among
the parties concerned on future peacekeeping arrangements in
Sierra Leone, and called upon the RUF and all other groups in
Sierra Leone to begin immediately to disband and give up their
arms in accordance with the provisions of the peace agreements,
said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Government of Sierra Leone and the Revolutionary United
Front signed the peace agreement on July 7 in Lome, capital of
Togo, putting an end to the eight-year civil war in the West
African country.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the agreement requires UNOMSIL perform
significantly expanded as well as new tasks, in close coordination
with ECOMOG, whose presence in Sierra Leone remains, in this
critical period, indispensable," said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan in his latest written report the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that, in addition to the major disarmament and
demobilization effort, the implementation of the Lome Peace
Agreement will require the presence of a substantial number of
peacekeepers throughout the country, together with the
deployment of additional United Nations military observers, in
mutually supporting roles," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Before the Council began the vote on the draft resolution,
Chen Xu, representative from the Chinese Mission to the United
Nations, said, "China has always supported the elected
government in Sierra Leone, and supported the peace process in
the country."
</P>
<P>
"We have, through various channels, provided various kinds of
assistance to the Sierra Leonean Government and to the West
African Military Observer Group," Chen said. "We will continue to
provide to that country various assistance within our
capabilities."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "we call upon the international community on the
basis of forward-looking principle to support the efforts to
carry out the peace agreement and help the Sierra Leonean people
to realize their national reconciliation and begin their
economic reconstruction at an early date," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
