<HEADLINE> Cyprus Journalists Sympathize with Turkey's Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Union of Cyprus Journalists
Friday expressed "grief and deep sympathy" to victims in Tuesday's
fatal quake in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to the Journalists Syndicate and the
Progressive Association of Journalists in Turkey, the Union
conveyed its "undivided solidarity and support" to rescue efforts
to help the victims of the catastrophic earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The Union also donated 1,000 U.S. dollars for the relief work.
</P>
<P>
Death toll has reached over 10,000 in the quake, measuring 7.4
degrees on Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
The quake, coming only days after a weaker tremor struck
Cyprus' Limassol town, has prompted many in Cyprus to put aside
enmity for its long-time rival Turkey.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Cyprus government took the unprecedented
step of promising medical aid to Turkey. President Glafcos
Clerides sent a message of condolences to his Turkish counterpart
Suleyman Demirel despite the fact that the two countries have no
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
The Astra radio, which is backed by the left AKEL party,
Thursday made an appeal for donation for Turkish people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
