<HEADLINE> More Needs To Be Done For Women: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Friday said more needs to be done to improve the status of
women.
</P>
<P>
He said this is the case although his party and government
have striven to put in place an environment that allows women to
fully participate in the political, social and economic affairs of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 1999 ruling Zanu (PF)
Women's League Congress in Harare, Mugabe called on women to take
advantage of the Constitutional Review Commission to make
contributions which would ensure that more rights for women be
enshrined in the new constitution.
</P>
<P>
"We want the status of both men and women to be equal to
improve the conditions of living in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe called on men to desist from interfering with what the
women desired by imposing candidates they wanted to fill certain
positions in the party.
</P>
<P>
He challenged parents and chiefs to re-examine some of the
traditional customs which oppressed women.
</P>
<P>
"There is need to work together with chiefs and parents to
promote the correct status of women," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said there is need to look into such issues where more
girls are dropped out of school than boys, stressing that women
need to be equipped with skills that would enable them to be
economically empowered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
