<HEADLINE> Ghana, Togo Affirm Peaceful Solution to Boundary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of Ghana
and Togo have affirmed the two countries' commitment to peacefully
resolving their boundary problems while respecting each others'
territorial integrity, Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
 They called their citizens living in the border areas to
desist from acts of provocation against each other and allow the
governments to work out amicable solutions to their problems.
</P>
<P>
 Nii Okaidja Adamafio, Ghana's Interior Minister and General
Sizing Walla, Togo's Minister of the Interior and Security, made
this affirmation while addressing the citizens of three border
districts in Ghana and Togo.
</P>
<P>
Okaidja appealed to Ghanaian border communities to exercise
restraint, assuring them that amicable solutions would be found to
such boundary and territorial problems.
</P>
<P>
The GNA did not specify when the minister made the speech.
</P>
<P>
 The Ghanaian minister called on peace-loving members of the
communities on both sides to exercise positive influences on those
bent on fomenting trouble.
</P>
<P>
 Walla added that it would be counter-productive for both
Ghana and Togo to resort to arms in settling their border
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
