<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Row on Wye Accord Still Exists: Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli negotiators
failed to iron out differences on the timetable of the
implementation of the Wye River accord, said senior Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat Friday.
</P>
<P>
The talks, held overnight for six hours in Jerusalem, were
"highly serious," Erekat told Palestine Radio, adding that the two
sides still disputed on the implementation of the Wye agreement,
release of Palestinian prisoners and the opening of Gaza seaport
and a safe passage.
</P>
<P>
No specific time was set for the resumption of the talks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Israeli government to make a political decision on
implementing the signed agreements with Palestinians as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
On some new suggestions by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Erekat said there is no need to further negotiate on or merge
later stages of the already-signed accords, adding that such
proposals were not raised during recent talks between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Israeli daily Ha'aretz reported on Thursday that Barak had
presented three main points to push forward the peace process,
namely:
</P>
<P>
- Start implementation of the Wye accord after some
mutually-accepted modifications from September 1 to early 2000;
</P>
<P>
- The two sides start marathon talks during the first week of
September on a framework or a declaration of principle of the
final status talks till the target date of early 2000;
</P>
<P>
- The two sides refrain from any unilateral moves that could
affect the status of the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
