<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Million Somalis Face Dismal Harvest: WFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Prolonged dry periods in
southern Somalia have put one million people to a situation of
dismal harvest, the United Nations World Food Program (WFP) said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Less than 130,000 tons of sorghum and maize are expected to be
harvested this year, against 101,760 tons in 1998, which was
especially low as a result of EL Nino floods and 205,850 tons
gathered in 1997, according to WFP statistics.
</P>
<P>
A recent assessment by international agencies indicated that
this year's cereal harvest in the east African country will only
just exceed that of 1998, which saw the lowest production in five
years, said WFP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
