<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Shoddy Construction, Lax Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 people have
been killed and over 45,000 injured in Tuesday's massive
earthquake in northwest Turkey. And the numbers are still rising
by the hour.
</P>
<P>
As rescue efforts for those 35,000 still believed trapped under
the rubble and relief work for quake survivors continued well into
the fourth day, the Turks pondered over the question: was it
merely by a stroke of bad luck that so many lives were claimed?
</P>
<P>
Maybe not, or at least it was not the whole story, some people
said.
</P>
<P>
Poor construction of the buildings was to be blamed for the
high death toll, said a seismologist who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
His claim might find evidence in our second visit to the
quake-hit Avcilar in west Istanbul, about 400 kilometers west of
Ankara, Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a residential area in Avcilar, we saw several buildings
reduced to debris while surrounding houses remained virtually
intact.
</P>
<P>
Since Turkey launched speedy economic drive in early 1980s,
the construction sector thrived as people tried to improve their
housing conditions and rural Turks poured into large cities by
the millions looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many contractors skimped on materials or used inferior cement
and concrete bars to cut down on costs. When the powerful
pre-dawn quake struck Tuesday, those jerrily-built houses
collapsed like stacks of playing cards.
</P>
<P>
A 50-some man, who claimed to be an architectural engineer
himself, told us, as rescuers were scrambling several meters away
the piles of rubble in search for about 10 people trapped inside,
that many of the houses pancaked down in the quake were built in
the 1980s or since.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers have lately been running articles critical of
government officials for their lax administration in enforcing
building codes. Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit had promised
a crackdown on unscrupulous builders.
</P>
<P>
Apart from shoddy houses, the government's initial
ineffectiveness in launching research and rescue works also
contributed to the heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
In a country known to major seismologic activities, "it is
incredible that the state apparatus was stunned for nearly 24
hours" after the quake hit the most populous areas and industrial
centers of the country, said the Turkish Daily News in its
editorial Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In many quake-hit areas, rescue apparatus like electric saws
used for cutting tangled steel were hardly available and
relatives or neighbors had to dig into the debris with bare hands
in search for trapped people.
</P>
<P>
After the quake hit early Tuesday morning, electricity and
water supplies in many parts of the country were cut off for about
24 hours. Traffic was also deadlocked as people driving cars were
trying to flee stricken areas, seriously hampering rescue works.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake, which was measured at 7.4 degrees
on the Richter scale and lasted for 45 seconds, was only 10
kilometers underground, thus aggravating the intensity of the
quake.
</P>
<P>
And, not unusual with seismologic activities, the catastrophe,
hitting at 3:02 a.m. (0002 GMT) Tuesday, occurred while most of
the people were sleeping, thus crushing tens of thousands of
people in their sound sleep.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-six aftershocks with magnitude over four degrees were
recorded so far since Tuesday's fatal quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
