<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Well-known Aid Worker Killed in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A well-known aid worker was
killed Thursday night in Hargeisa Yarey Village, 35 km south of
Jilib district of the Middle Jubba region, Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Qasim Aden Egal, the head of the Medicine Sans Frontier of
Spain in Gedo and Lower Jubba regions of southern Somalia, was
killed by unidentified gunmen who intercepted his vehicle at an
illegal roadblock outside the village.
</P>
<P>
The aid worker, who had been the former Director-General of
Somalia's Health Ministry during the last regime, was driving a
Landcruiser vehicle on his way to Bardera district of Gedo after
his routine business trip from the southern port town of Kismaio
which he left Thursday afternoon, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the killing is not known, but eye-witnesses said
the gunmen aimed at looting the well-sought vehicle. Landcruisers
are very much liked by Somali gunmen because they are of high
value and can be turned into battle wagons.
</P>
<P>
After a little hesitation following the order of the occupants
to get down, the gunmen opened fire. The first bullet hit Egal in
the heart and he died on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The killers reportedly belong to the Marehan clan of General
Omar Hajji Massaleh, Chairman of the Somali National Front which
together with other allied forces captured the town of Kismaio
from General Hirsi Morgan. Masalleh, however, described the
killing as an unfortunate incident and purely banditry act not
related to any kind of clan animosity.
</P>
<P>
Even so, local and international aid workers have felt more
and more insecure in Somalia when there are serious humanitarian
crises in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
