<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore's Trade Expands by 8.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade rose
for three consecutive months in July, increasing by 8.4 percent
compared with a year earlier, according to statistics released by
the Trade Development Board (TDB) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The growth reflected the continued strength of the global
electronics demand and the further improvement in economic
conditions of the crisis-hit Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports (NODX) expanded by 11.5 percent over
the same month of last year, maintaining a positive trend which
started in April 1999 and marginally better than the 10.3 percent
growth registered in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Compared to July last year, non-oil re-exports (NORX) fell by
3.5 percent, the third consecutive month of milder decline as
compared to the double-digit contractions in the preceding months.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports expanded by 13.4 percent, following a healthy
growth of 11.0 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall improvement in trade performance, there
were isolated export segments and markets which remained
depressed.
</P>
<P>
After a 9.1 percent contraction in June, domestic exports of
printers remained in the negative territory, contracting by 4.0
percent in July if compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
NODX to Hong Kong continued its downward trend, contracting by
15.6 percent in July over the same month of 1998.
</P>
<P>
As to the performance of key trade components, the improvement
in NODX mirrored the continued recovery of electronics exports and
the healthy growth in non-electronic exports.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports of electronic products increased for the third
consecutive month, by 8.6 percent in July compared to the same
month of 1998. Domestic exports of non-electronic products
expanded for the fifth consecutive month, growing by 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase continued to come from strong growth in domestic
exports of pharmaceuticals and intermediate compounds to the EU
and disc media products to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Compared with July 1998, domestic oil exports grew by 6.2
percent in July 1999, moderating marginally from the 6.9 percent
for June. The increase in oil price continued to contribute to the
growth of oil exports in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil re-exports (NORX) fell by 3.5 percent in July, the
third consecutive month of more moderate decline as compared to
the double-digit declines in the preceding months.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports (excluding aircraft and ships) grew by 13.4
percent, largely due to increases in imports of ICs, parts of
semiconductors, capacitors, cellular phones and radio phones,
parts of CTCs and radios, and printed circuits.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same month of last year, among the top five
markets, only NODX to Hong Kong remained in the doldrums in July
with a contraction of 15.6 percent while the remaining four, the
U.S., the EU, Malaysia and Japan, continued to expand during the
month.
</P>
<P>
In particular, NODX to the U.S., the EU, Malaysia and Japan in
July rose 7.6, 8.3, 9.2 and 41.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
NODX to the emerging markets continued to expand in July,
growing by 6.8 percent following an 8.7 percent growth in the
previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
