<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (roundup)German Ruling Party Calls For State Intervene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20(Xinhua)-Amid a drastic decline of electricity
price caused by the bitter competition among domestic power
providers, spokespersons of Germany's ruling Social Democratic
Party (SPD) on Friday urged the federal authorities to regulate
the market.
</P>
<P>
The continuously dropping power price, they said, would hinder
the employment of environment-friendly technologies in electricity
generation, and would leave those small power plants under huge
market pressure.
</P>
<P>
Volker Jung, SPD's parliamentary spokesman on energy issues,
told the Deutsche Presse Agentur (DPA) news agency in Berlin, that
federal regulation was needed "to secure a reasonable entrance
into German electricity network, both for those small power plants
and for those market-newcomers."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was also quoted as calling for more renewable
energy and power-warm coupling in German electricity market.
</P>
<P>
Jung's colleague on environmental policy Christoph Matschie
approved the initiative by suggesting the Federal Cartel Office to
interfere the price war.
</P>
<P>
"Eventually the federal government must keep equal chance for
all the electricity providers," he told the Deutschland Radio in
Berlin, adding that Germany's anti-trust authorities, the Federal
Cartel Office, would be a suitable institution to take over the
regulation.
</P>
<P>
After German government partly loosened the regional monopoly
on electricity market, the price war broke out earlier this summer
when large concerns such as RWE and PRUSSAG announced to cut power
price and to provide electricity for nationwide customers.
</P>
<P>
In latest developments, Bayernwerk, power provider in the
southern state of Bavaria and Germany's third largest energy
concern, on this Tuesday declared to sell cheap electricity all
over the country after September 1. And Bewag, the company
supplying the capital Berlin with electricity, said on Friday it
would cut power price by at least 10 per cent.
</P>
<P>
Though most enterprises and common citizens might benefit from
the price war, small power plants, outcome of the regional
monopoly policy and mostly generating power only for one city,
were under the pressure of market. Plans of corporate fusion and
staff lay-off in this branch were widely reported over the summer.
</P>
<P>
The situation aroused worries inside Germany's ruling
coalition, including SPD that struggles against the high jobless
rate and its junior partner, the Greens party that boasts
environmental protection. They said renewable energy would have no
chance with much higher production cost, and some control by the
government might be necessary.
</P>
<P>
Michael Mueller, deputy chief of SPD's parliamentary fraction,
warned against an uncontrolled war on electricity price earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
"If our argument is only about the price, the ecologically
meaningful power generator and the power-warm coupling will have
no chance to survive," he was quoted as telling the "Tagesspiegel"
newspaper in Berlin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Mueller, by now there are 50 to 90 small municipal
power plants to be sold. If this situation develops, he added, one
day German market will overflow with cheap power from the east
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The arguments did not convince Germany's opposites, the
conservative Christian Democrats (CDU) and the tiny Free
Democratic Party (FDP). The two prefer a free electricity market
with less governmental intervene.
</P>
<P>
Paul Friedhoff, FDP's parliamentary spokesman for energy
policy, said on Friday that the government should open the market
more. Those small power plants must seize the chance in the
rapidly expanding electricity market, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Ugandan Students to Study in China Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 11 Ugandan students
will go to pursue their studies in several universities in China,
bringing the number of students who studied and are about to study
in China to 200.
</P>
<P>
Rwendeire Abel, state minister of higher education, made the
revelation at a party organized for the 11 students by the Chinese
Embassy here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
They will study computer sciences, medical sciences and
electrical engineering, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged to the students to take advantage of this rare
opportunity to study in China and hope that they will contribute
more to the development of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Uganda Zhang Xujiang said that China
would provide more scholarships to Ugandan students in the near
future and promote the exchange of visiting scholars.
</P>
<P>
This is being done because it is in the interest of both
countries, the ambassador stressed. 
