<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Open Up an Inland Port in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RNA quoted Vincent Biruta, Rwandan Minister of Transport and
Telecommunications as saying that the inland port will be opened
at Isaka in northwestern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He said that Isaka dry port managed by the Tanzanian Railways
Cooperation (TRC), is strategically important in serving the rich
agricultural, commercial and industrialized hinterland of Rwanda,
the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Burundi, Uganda and
northwestern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Isaka will provide a holiday point for a containerized traffic,
thus alleviating the necessity to travel to Dar-es-Salaam.
</P>
<P>
"The dry port is set to provide an efficient sea link at
competitive tariff, rapid transit time, safety and security of
cargo, easy documentation and proactive customer services,"
minister Biruta underlined.
</P>
<P>
The conversion of Isaka container terminal into a dry port will
make it quite a viable gateway for Rwanda's sea-borne trade.
</P>
<P>
While addressing Rwandan business people, Cassian Ngamiro, head
of the Tanzanian delegation which visited Rwanda early this week
underscored that Isaka dry port has adequate capacity to handle
all types of cargoes, the timely processing of documents, timing
of nominated vessels for shipments and assured safety and security
of cargo.
</P>
<P>
"It will reduce the costs of transport in terms of time saved,
documentation, reduced burden on return of empty containers and
provide a competitive route tariff," Ngamiro stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan business community hailed the initiative by both
countries, saying that it will reduce the transportation costs by
40% which will further reduce the prices of goods.
</P>
<P>
Isaka dry port is connected to Kigali, capital of Rwanda by the
tarmac road at a distance of 480 kms which is less costly compared
to the former route Dar-es-salaam-Kigali which is 982 kms long.
</P>
</TEXT>
