<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roman Catholic Bishop in Court for Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The former Roman Catholic Bishop
Augustin Misago of southwestern Gikongoro Diocese was called to
the Kigali Criminal Court for the first time, Rwanda News Agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Misago faces five charges, including genocide and other crimes
against humanity, the creation of armed militia, complicity in
genocide and non-assistance to a person in danger. If found
guilty, he may be placed in the category one of genocide criminals
whose punishment is death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the prosecution finished reading charges against
him, the trial was immediately suspended following a disagreement
between the defense council and the prosecution on whether the
prelate should be legally detained or not.
</P>
<P>
The defense also requested the court to secure provisional
release to the accused because of his allegedly ill-health. This
prompted the court to hold a short session at the end of which it
announced that its decision on the above disagreement will be made
public on August 25, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he was ready for being tried, Misago said: ''I'm
not prepared for trial, because I did not have enough time to read
and understand my case file.''
</P>
<P>
The prosecution rejected the arguments put forward by Misago
and his three lawyers, saying that they were resorting to dilatory
tactics aimed at securing provisional release for the prelate.
</P>
<P>
Misago, 56 and a Hutu, was arrested on April 14 this year, just
one week after the fifth commemoration of the 1994 genocide at
Kibeho, 100 kms south of Kigali, capital of Rwanda during which he
was accused by genocide survivors of having played a leading role
in the massacre of Tutsis and moderate Hutus which claimed the
lives of more than 500,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
