<HEADLINE> Britain Signals Sinn Fein to Stay in N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain signaled Friday that it
would not expel the IRA's political wing from a planned review of
Northern Ireland's stalled peace accord even if it decides that
the guerrilla group has broken its two-year-old ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam hinted that any breach
might be penalized by suspension of a scheme for early release of
jailed IRA members.
</P>
<P>
"She explained the consequence of her finding a breach of the
ceasefire would be an effect on the prisoner release program," the
Reuters quoted a spokeswoman at Mowlam's Northern Ireland Office
(NIO) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam, after receiving security briefings about recent
incidents, has spent this week grappling with the thorny issue of
whether the IRA has breached a truce that is pivotal to peace
hopes -- and if so whether sanctions should be imposed on its Sinn
Fein political arm.
</P>
<P>
But amid calls by some of Sinn Fein's pro-British opponents for
its expulsion from the peace process, the NIO said there was "no
automatic process" for excluding it from a review of the peace
accord by U.S. mediator George Mitchell next month.
</P>
<P>
Last year's landmark Good Friday peace accord has been crippled
by wrangling between rival parties and Britain and Ireland have
called in Mitchell in the hope he can ease problems about
disarmament and lack of trust between politicians. 
</P>
