<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ally Clashes Overshadow Fragile Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda, best allies
in the region but supporting different factions of the main rebel
group in the Congo, turned guns against each other in Kisangani in
northeastern Congo recently, overshadowing the fragile peace
process aimed at resolving the year-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
The clashes, which reportedly erupted on Saturday and lasted
till Tuesday, was for the control of an airport in Kisangani where
Ugandan troops were greatly outnumbered and out gunned. Dozens of
soldiers died in the exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
This negative twist of event would further complicate the Congo
issue and fan hostilities between the two factions of the
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) Kampala and Kigali are
supporting, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda, out of different strategies and tactics,
chose to support opposing factions of the RCD after it split on
May 19 following a leadership wrangle. Even before the shoot-out,
a verbal battle had been fought between Uganda and Rwanda, in
which both parties had accused each other of backing the wrong
side.
</P>
<P>
This fighting between friends alerted again the international
community who had felt a bit relaxed after the Lusaka cease-fire
agreement endorsed by six African countries on July 10 because it
threatened to nip the fresh peace process in the bud.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the incident, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan announced that the two belligerent countries had breached
the cease-fire agreement they had just inked and that it greatly
undermined the peace efforts the international community is making
in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The just concluded 19th summit of the Southern African
Development Community had invited Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and his Rwandan counterpart Pasteur Bizimungu to discuss
the issue of the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Both presidents
aired their views about the conflict and put forth their
suggestions for resolutions during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity Salim
Ahmed Salim and Congolese Foreign Minister Yerodia Ndombase, who
represents President Laurent Kabila at the meeting, welcomed the
cease-fire agreement between Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The wrangling among rebel groups over representation in Lusaka
led to failure to sign the cease-fire pact. And Uganda-Rwanda
conflict created further hurdles to the realization of real peace
in the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Although both sides agreed to stop fighting and began to smile
at each other, Kisangani is still shrouded in a tense and hostile
atmosphere. So it is still too early to say the cease-fire is
holding and both sides would willingly bury the hatchet. The
impact of the fighting on the peace process is negative and
enduring, observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
