<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges to Promote Solution for Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
pledged that the U.S. would continue to promote a solution to the
Cyprus issue based on a bizonal, bicommunal federation, the Cyprus
News Agency (CNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In his bi-monthly report to the U.S. Congress on the Cyprus
issue, Clinton recalled that during NATO's Washington summit on
the 50th anniversary of the military bloc, he "met with Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel and Greek Premier Constantinos Simitis
to underscore the importance of a just and lasting solution for
all Cypriots."
</P>
<P>
He said that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright conveyed a
similar message during talks with her Greek and Turkish
counterparts on the possibility of resuming the Cyprus peace
talks in the fall.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the U.S. would continue efforts to promote
"a settlement based on a bizonal, bicommunal federation."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to settle the Cyprus issue have been stalled after
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash set preconditions for the
recognition of the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
He is also demanding that the peace negotiations would result
in establishing a "confederation of two states."
</P>
<P>
The U.N., the Cyprus government and all key players in the
peace efforts have rejected the demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
