<HEADLINE> Sampras Forced to Retire Against Spadea at RCA Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras saw his 24-match
winning streak come to an end when a right hip flexor strain
forced him to retire after two sets of his quarterfinal matchup
with fellow American Vincent Spadea at the RCA Championships in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
Sampras dropped the first set 6-4 but rebounded to take the
second 6-3. The injury really began to bother the world's top-
ranked player and he opted against playing the decisive third set.
</P>
<P>
"I felt it after I hit that overhead (early in the second set),
" Sampras said. "I hit just kind of -- I kind of felt it go. I
didn't feel the shot just after it, I felt it definitely twinged
my -- it was deep in my hip flexor."
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who had won this event three times, is hoping that the
injury will not sideline him for long. The U.S. Open begins August
30.
</P>
<P>
"I'm hoping three or four days of just rest and treatment and
taking care of it, and hope I can start hitting by the middle of
the week."
</P>
<P>
Spadeea advances to face unseeded Sebastian Grosjean of France
in the semifinals. Grosjean surprised third seed Gustavo Kuerten
of Brazil 6-4, 6-3. Grosjean is a hardcourt stalwart who reached
the
finals at this years's Lipton Championships.
</P>
<P>
In the lone matchup of seeded players, 11th seed Nicolas
Lapentti of Ecuador routed fourth seed Carlos Moya of Spain 6-1,6-
2. Lapentti will meet the Netherlands Jan Siemerink, who walked
into the semifinals on Thursday, when second-seeded Patrick Rafter
of Australia pulled out with a shoulder injury. 
</P>
