<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Air Force Conducts Last Stage of Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Warplanes of Iran's air force
held the last stage of air-to-surface firing exercises
code-namde "Heydar Karrar" (Brave Lion) Saturday in Shabester
area in the northwestern province of East Azarbaijan.
</P>
<P>
One hundred fighter planes and bombers from the country's
various air bases took part in the three-day maneuvers, in
which 300 sorties were carried out, according to the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA).
</P>
<P>
The fighters and bombers conducted low-altitude bombing, and
fired air-to-surface missiles and machine guns. They included
the U.S.-made F-14s, F-5s, F-4s, F-7s, and Russia-made Su-24s
and Mig-29s, the local Persian-language daily "Kayhan" (Worl
d) reported.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted an Air force commander as saying that a remarkable
achievement of Iranian technicians is their installing of equipment
on the F-14s to enable them to act as multi-purpose bombers.
</P>
<P>
The project for upgrading F-14 fighter planes showed the
air force has reached self-sufficiency and it has no
limitation in maintenance and upgrading the fighter planes as
well as manufacturing modern equipment, the commander said.
</P>
<P>
Military officials said one of the main purposes of the
drilling was to test the reliability of Iran-made spare parts for
maintenance of U.S.-made warplanes as it had been difficult for
Iran to procure such spare parts due to U.S.-imposed military
and economic sanctions. 
</P>
