<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Deny Children Involvement in War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
militia Saturday rejected the accusations by the United Nations
that it was sending juveniles to fight against the opposition
forces.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's senior official responsible for information, Mulla
Amir Muttaqi, was quoted by the Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) as
saying that the claim by the U.N is "totally false and an
allegation."
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan (IEA) has never recruited
young men to its ranks and will never do so," Muttaqi said.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. official Friday voiced concern over the growing
recruitment of students from Islamic schools in Pakistan into the
ranks of the Taliban militia in its current war against the
country's beleaguered opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
A large number of the students are under the age of 18, said
Louis-Georges Arsenault, UNICEF representative for Afghanistan, at
a news briefing in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
According to AIP, Muttaqi accused the U.N. of "making untrue
statements in order to defame and pressure the IEA" in a bid "to
heighten the propaganda campaign against the Islamic Emirate."
</P>
</TEXT>
