<HEADLINE> Taliban Say Willing to Discuss Osama Issue With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
militia Saturday repeated its offer for talks to the United States
to resolve the long-standing issue of the expulsion of Osama bin
Laden, the alleged terrorist.
</P>
<P>
"Differences could not be solved through force," said a Taliban
official statement issued in Kabul on the first anniversary of the
American missile attack on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned the attack, urging Washington to
refrain from repeating the mistakes committed by the British and
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
The United States fired around 70 Tomahawk cruise missiles on
August 20 last year on the eastern Afghan town of Khost in a bid
to kill Osama, who survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi dissident has been accused by the United States of
involvement in the bomb blasts at the U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Taliban senior official Amir Khan Muttaqi Thursday condemned
"the naked aggression" by the U.S. last year and said any other
U.S. attack on Afghanistan would be a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban militia is ready to settle all issues,
including Osama, with the United States through talks.
</P>
<P>
Amid renewed fears of fresh strikes by Washington, Taliban have
resisted all pressures to evict Osama because of his participation
in the Afghan Jihad (holy war) against the Soviet occupation in
the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
