<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Says Taliban Attack Repulsed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan opposition alliance
said Saturday they had repulsed a heavy attack by the Taliban on
northeastern Takhar province, a key supply route for the Panjsher
valley -- the stronghold of opposition commander Ahmad Shah
Masood.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from the Afghan capital of Kabul quoted
opposition spokesman Abdullah (one name) as saying that the attack
on Takhar had been launched from three directions Friday from the
neighboring Kunduz province which is controlled by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"The attack, backed by helicopter gunships and tanks, started
around dawn and continued till late into the night," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban troops were hit back after their initial advance
and lost the areas they had taken including some of their own
positions, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 42 Taliban soldiers were killed and dozens of others
wounded during the fighting, said Abdullah, adding that seven from
the opposition side were killed and 15 wounded.
</P>
<P>
No independent confirmation and comments from the Taliban were
immediately available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
