<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Buenos Aires Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday rejected claims
by Argentine Vice President Carlos Ruckauf that its diplomats had
been involved in a bombing attack on a Jewish center in Buenos
Aires five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid-Reza Asefi dismissed the
accusations as "unfounded," saying Ruckauf's "repeated,
undocumented and irresponsible claims were aimed at creating
ballyhoo against Iran."
</P>
<P>
Iran's cultural attache to Argentina was accused of being
involved in the bomb explosion in 1994 which killed 88 people and
injured 159 others.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian national, Manouchehr Motamer, offered some
information after the bombing to Argentine authorities claiming
that Iranian diplomats were behind the attack.
</P>
<P>
However, Argentina failed to find enough evidence to support
the accusations over the past five years, and Iran has repeatedly
denied any involvement in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Asefi turned the table on Ruckauf, who was interior minister of
Argentine at the time of the bombing, accusing him of
mismanagement in the past and cover-up at present.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that Ruckauf ... who failed to justify his
mismanagement ... now is trying to cover up past weaknesses during
his tenure as interior minister, by raising such unfounded
accusations," Asefi was quoted by the official Islamic Republic
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Argentina suffered great setbacks
after the bombing, with both sides lowering their diplomatic
representation in each other's capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
