<HEADLINE> 6 Killed, 32 Injured in Bus-Truck Collision in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A bus carrying 63 workers rammed
into the back of a truck on Saturday in Egypt and fell into a
roadside canal, killing six men.
</P>
<P>
Another 32 workers were injured, the country's Middle East News
Agency reported, adding that the injured were in stable condition
at a hospital in the governorate of Giza.
</P>
<P>
Investigators determined that the bus swerved to avoid an
oncoming car on the opposite lane, the agency said. The driver,
Abdel-Rahim Mahmoud, lost control of the bus, hit the truck and
slid into the canal, it added.
</P>
<P>
The construction workers of the Arab Contractors Company were
on their way to the construction site in the 6th of October City,
30 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The driver of the truck, Hamada Mohammed Ali, had fled the
scene, but was later captured. He was being held for questioning,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents are common in Egypt due to high speed and
violation of traffic rules and regulations. Official estimation
put the annual death toll at 6,000 in the road accidents.
</P>
<P>
A government committee is looking into the rising number of
fatalities on Egyptian roads, especially rural roads, which the
local media have dubbed "roads of death." 
</P>
</TEXT>
