<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expedition Boat Collides With Ice Floe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 21 (Xinhua)-- A boat from the Chinese
Arctic Expedition ship Snow Dragon collided with an ice floe on
the Arctic Ocean this morning and was seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
No one was aboard the boat when it crashed into the four-meter
thick, football-field-size ice floe.
</P>
<P>
The 30-meter-long expedition boat The Great Wall was at anchor
on the sea when the incident occurred, as it was prepared to ferry
expedition members and equipment to a temporary observation
station on the ice.
</P>
<P>
The floating ice appeared all of a sudden, striking the boat
violently and pushing it toward the Snow Dragon, said Chen Bo, a
biologist who was preparing to carry instruments to the boat as
the collision took place.
</P>
<P>
"The boat was crushed out of shape, and then the ice continued
to float far away with almost no loss," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The sea around the ship was shrouded in a thick fog at the time
and visibility was less than 100 meters, a member of the
expedition team said, adding that "the thick fog hid everything,
including the quietly approaching ice floe."
</P>
<P>
"It was only two minutes from the time we saw the ice coming to
the time of the collision," said Boatswain Wu Lin. "The ice was
coming at so high a speed that we had no time to use the crane to
lift up the boat."
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the expedition team had to use another boat,
the Zhongshan No. 1, to carry out the unfinished task of The Great
Wall.
</P>
<P>
The accident has had some negative impact on transport
effectiveness, since the substitute boat is less advanced than The
Great Wall, according to Captain Yuan Shaohong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Arrest Two for Attempted Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Police in northeast China's
Liaoning Province have arrested two men suspected of attempted
murder who had been hired by a convicted economic criminal.
</P>
<P>
The two, both released prisoners, were hired by Li Zhongquan,
former head of a district branch of the Fuxin City Public Security
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Li had been sentenced to 12 years in prison for serious
economic crime, but was serving his prison term outside under
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Li and his wife reportedly hired the two to kill Chen Ming, a
city discipline inspector who was one of the principal persons to
deal with Li's case.
</P>
<P>
On July 1 of this year, the two men stabbed Chen in the chest
while he just came out from his home to go to his office. Chen's
lung was seriously injured and was taken to a nearby hospital
where he was recovered after 45 percent of his wounded lung was
removed.
</P>
<P>
Seven days later police arrested Li in Beijing and his wife in
Inner Mongolia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
