<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Ruling Party Holds Grand Procession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's ruling People's
Alliance (PA) Saturday staged a massive procession in Colombo to
mark the coalition's five years in power despite warnings of Tamil
rebels' suicide bomb attacks.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of men and women from all walks of life
attended the procession, which was described as a grand national
ceremony to mark the millennium.
</P>
<P>
About 160 colorful floats were driven along the parade
depicting the government's achievements during the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
The parade will be followed by a mass rally in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the event is "Five-year vision -- vision for the
new century." President Chandrika Kumaratunga is expected to make
a policy statement at the rally enunciating her government's
vision to herald an era of peace and unity, enlightenment and
modernity in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The National Intelligence Bureau warned the week before that
over 20 suicide bombers of Tamil rebels of Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had infiltrated into Colombo recently to carry
out suicide missions, and that the situation in the capital city
was not advisable for large crowds to congregate.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting since 1983 for a Tamil homeland in
Sri Lanka's north and east, have been blamed by the government for
carrying out a suicide bomb attack which killed leading Tamil
lawmaker Neelan Thiruchelvam in Colombo at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Former president Ranasinghe Premadasa and several others were
killed in 1993's May Day procession in Colombo by Tamil rebels'
suicide bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
