<HEADLINE> Institutional Reform for SADC Enjoys Priority: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Priority will be given to the
institutional reform for the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) during the time when Mozambique becomes the
chairman nation of the regional body, Mozambican Foreign Minister
Leonardo Simao has said.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility study will be conducted first toward this goal, he
was quoted as announcing at a press conference by Saturday's
Noticias newspaper. Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano was
elected last Wednesday as the new chairman of the 14-member
regional body.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that "recent operation of the SADC
shows that its set-up needs reform, which includes its
secretariat". This was required at the 19th summit of the
regional organization held last week in Maputo, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Discussion will be conducted on what is SADC and what is its
aim," he said, noting that the regional body's strategic plan
lacks "visibility".
</P>
<P>
One of the SADC's aims, he said, is to help resolve the
conflicts existing in the region at present. Mozambique will play
a bigger role in this field, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
