<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Shifts Stand on Niger's Military Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), Lansana
Kouyate Friday in Abuja canvassed international support for Niger
Republic, implying the regional body's softening of stance
against the country's military authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to Kouyate, ECOWAS, which condemned the April 9 coup
d'etat in the country, was shifting its stand and moving to
accept the prevailing reality by supporting its on-going
democratization process, reported the Guardian, a Nigerian
newspaper on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The military government led by former head of the presidential
guard, Major Dauda Wanke, which emerged after the assassination
of former president Ibrahim Mainassara, has been battling for
international recognition since the April putsch.
</P>
<P>
"We are being realistic in the belief that the authorities in
Niger would abide by their promise to hold presidential elections
in November and hand over to elected civilians," Kouyate
declared.
</P>
<P>
He said that the organization, which was at the forefront in
the campaign for the international isolation of the regime of
Wanke, had also found its efforts undermined by some member
states.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said the latest support by ECOWAS was intended to
"encourage the on-going democratization" in that country to
ensure that it did not relapse into another era of military rule.
</P>
<P>
He promised to visit Niger to evaluate its democratization and
stressed that the sub-region was still committed to discouraging
coup plotters. The country is shopping for one billion French CFA
to hold elections ahead of the handover to civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
