<HEADLINE> Lagos Police Crack-Down Yields Result </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Lagos state, Nigeria's economic
hub, recently has seen a drop of violent crimes with the adoption
of new security measures and effective use of new logistics, said
the state's police Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Saturday quoted
Lagos State Police Commissioner Michael Okiro as saying that the
police's efforts last week had led to the arrest of some gang
leaders.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a week-long crack-down on criminals led to
the arrest of no fewer than 15 robbery suspects.
</P>
<P>
Six double barred guns, two pump action rifles and 209 bullets
were retrieved from suspects in Lagos during the week.
</P>
<P>
"Lagos is now visibly peaceful," the police said, noting
however, that " there is no way that the police can completely
eradicate crime."
</P>
<P>
But Okiro assured Lagos residents of police determination "to
keep it at the minimum".  
</P>
</TEXT>
