<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lagos Traffic Accidents Claim 315 Lives This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- About 315 persons died in 1,702
accidents involving 2,245 vehicles between January and June this
year in Lagos State, Nigeria's commercial center, reported a
Nigerian newspaper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 1,050 sustained injuries of varying degrees during the
same period reported the Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lagos State Sector Commander of the Federal
Road Safety Commission (FRSC) Olagunju Kayode as saying that the
accident figure is seven percent higher than that of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
He, however, blamed the increase on low level of FRSC
operations on the first quarter of the year, generated by the
crises on motor-parks, indiscipline on the highways by motorists,
bad roads, alcohol and bad vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons adduced by the FRSC boss are impatience, night
travels and general indiscipline by road users, including
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the trend, Kayode said the commission would embark
on intensive patrol of highways and public enlightenment
activities.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to be employed include involvement of the
police, state and local governments as well as other interest
groups, in decongesting
Lagos roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
