<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Innovation in Production Process Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Levels of productivity and
competitiveness in Zimbabwean industries will continue to fall
unless a continuous process of innovation is implemented, the
Center for Innovation and Enterprise Development (CIED) said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The CIED is part of an international initiative in Africa to
foster innovation and development of technological capability for
industrial competitiveness primarily among small to medium
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A CIED report issued here Saturday said that lack of a culture
of innovation in improving products had resulted in the industry
failing to sustain competition both locally and regionally.
</P>
<P>
"At the micro-level, successful competition requires quality of
products, superior process of technology, and a proper
organization of production," it said.
</P>
<P>
"This can only be attained if a wide array of domestic linkages
between the users and producers are formulated," the center said.
</P>
<P>
The center recently introduced its services to Zimbabwe to
assist firms in identifying appropriate local and external
networking partners in innovative activities as well as to provide
training programs for firms across the country in the specific
sub-sectors.
</P>
<P>
The center is financed by the International Development
Research Center of Canada with project management services
provided by the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
