<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One of First Giant Panda Triplets Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Professor Zhang Hemin, a giant panda specialist,
at around two o'clock this morning, a worker who was on round-the-
clock care duty found that one cub had been deserted by mother,
and the cub, who weighed 137 grams at birth, was already dead.
</P>
<P>
A medical examination showed that three-day-old little cub died
of a fatal bladder disorder, said Professor Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The three cubs were born on the morning of August 18. The
oldest of the cubs weighs 156 grams, and the middle one, 137.7
grams. They are the first recorded giant panda triplets in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The youngest surviving cub was being tended to by the mother,
and the eldest cub is being taken care of by the center staff
members. The two remaining cubs are said to be in good health.
</P>
<P>
Normally, giant pandas give birth to one or two cubs each time.
China used artificial insemination to produce the first giant
panda cub born in captivity in 1963.
</P>
<P>
The 30-hectare center, located at the Wolong Nature Reserve in
the northern suburbs of Chengdu, was developed by the Chinese
government and the World Wildlife Fund (WWF) in 1980 and has
successfully bred 24 giant pandas since 1991, of which 15 survived.
</P>
<P>
There are only about 1,000 giant pandas, both in captivity and
in the wild, remaining in the world, 80 percent of which live in
the mountains around the Sichuan Basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
