<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symposium Marking Return of Macao to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Over 50 experts from the Chinese
inland areas and Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan regions today
attended a symposium marking the return of Macao to China in the
city of Zhuhai, one of China's five special economic zones, in
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the China Foreign Affairs
College and the office of the Zhuhai Special Economic Zone
Newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed issues including the significance of the
return of Macao, the economic development of Macao after the
return and its economic relations with the Chinese inland areas,
and Hong Kong and Taiwan regions, economic cooperation between
Macao and Zhuhai, as well as the reunification of China and
relations between the Chinese inland areas and Taiwan province.
</P>
<P>
Those taking part unanimously denounced Lee Teng-hui's the "two-
state" and the "special state-to-state " remarks.
</P>
<P>
Yang Fuchang, President of the China Foreign Affairs College,
said that just when all Chinese are busy making preparations to
greet the return of Macao to the motherland in December, Lee Teng-
hui threw out his "special state-to-state" remark on July 9, which
severely damaged cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
"Unity and reunification have long been a fine tradition of the
Chinese nation, and safeguarding national unity has always been at
the core of China's politics and culture, " said Yang, who is a
former vice foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui's "two-state" remark violates international law
and has been rebuked by the international community, Yang
continued, adding that the return of Macao demonstrates that the
reunification of China is a strong tide which no one can block,
and Lee's remark will be doomed to being swept away by history.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jiaji, a veteran diplomat, said in an article that Lee's "
special state-to-state" remark violates the "one China" principle
and goes against the consensus on this principle reached by both
sides of the Straits before the 1992 meeting between Wang Daohan,
President of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits (ARATS) and Chairman Koo Chen-fu of the Straits Exchanges
Foundation (SEF).
</P>
<P>
"The principle of 'one China' is the foundation of contacts,
exchanges, and dialogue between two sides of the Taiwan Straits,
and Lee Teng-hui has taken a very dangerous step toward splitting
up the motherland by throwing out his 'special state-to-state'
remark, as these remarks destroy the foundation of cross-Straits
relations and harms the gradually stabilizing nature of these
relations," said the veteran diplomat.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Xiangduo, a history professor at Dongwu University in
Taiwan, said Lee Teng-hui's remarks are fraudulent, and Lee
misguides the Taiwan people and will eventually be spurned by them.
</P>
</TEXT>
