<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Saturday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- According to the United Nations, 40,000 people were killed
by the earthquake which took place in Izmit in northwest Turkey on
Tuesday. Four days after the earthquake, the hope for finding the
survivors is very small. The Turkish government said that 10,000
are confirmed dead, while many are still buried in the rubbles of
tens of thousands of houses.
</P>
<P>
-- The actions of intimidation by small groups of Albanians
against the Serbs and Gypsies still remaining in Kosovo are
attaining an alarming situation, according to U.N. High Commission
for Refugees. The U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Kosovo (KFOR) is
trying to protect the Kosovars of non-Albanian ethnicity, mainly
women and the elderly, in isolated places of hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- While the latest provisionary account of death toll from the
earthquake in Turkey now stands at 10,000, the U.N. fears that 35,
000 people are still buried in the rubbles. One in three of the
population living in the earthquake zone is affected, said Turkish
government who made the estimation by accounting the destroyed
houses from the air.
</P>
<P>
-- The movement of merger-acquisition is accelerating in the
world. The restructuring of the banking sector of Japan gave birth
to a largest bank in the world on Friday. In France, a project to
re-group three banks (BNP, Societe General and Paribas) has been
launched for six months and is yet to be completed. 
</P>
