<HEADLINE> Turkey Asks for Malaysian Contributions to Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has requested for
contributions from Malaysians to alleviate problems faced by its
earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians could send in their contributions, either in cash or
kind such as medical equipment and blankets to the embassy here,
Attila G. Kizilarslan, Commercial Counselor of the Turkish
Embassy, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
The disaster was far beyond the capacity of any country or
nation to handle alone, Attila said, adding the quake was
considered to be one of the most powerful in this century with the
number of directly affected people to be around one million.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish government has released a list of urgently needed
materials to be used for immediate requirement of survivors and a
number of countries including Malaysia has responded to the
request and decided to send assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Attila expressed the Turkish government's gratitude to the
Malaysian government for sending a 24-member rescue team from its
Special Malaysian Disaster Assistance and Rescue Team which left
for Ankara Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi announced
Friday that Malaysia would extend financial aid to Turkey and was
considering other forms of aid for the earthquake-hit country.
</P>
</TEXT>
