<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Progress in Poverty Reduction Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of poor households in
Vietnam has dropped from 70 percent to 30 percent since the 1980s,
Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The progress was shown in a survey made by Vietnam's Ministry
of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs with support from the
Danish government, the World Bank and The United Nations
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that trading centers such as Ho Chi Minh
City, Dong Nai and Vung Tau with relatively well developed
infrastructure are the wealthiest in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Mekong Delta is the country's second most prosperous area.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed that Vietnam's battle to beat hunger
and poverty is far from winning.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 4,800 households in Vietnam's seven economic
regions found that former Region 4 and the northern midlands are
the poorest areas.
</P>
<P>
Between 37 and 51 percent of the families in these areas live
in makeshift housing.
</P>
<P>
The poorest people live in areas with poor economic and social
infrastructure and most of the people living in such areas are not
part of the majority Kinh population.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is now listed at 122 in the world's total of 174
countries for life expectancy, education and job creation.
</P>
<P>
To raise its standing, the Vietnamese government has launched a
program to eliminate chronic hunger and poverty by the year 2010
and increase this decade's per capita income eight to ten times by
2020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
