<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Open to Charter Change Talks With Critics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Saturday he is open to talks with political and
church leaders to enlighten them on the issue involving his call
for economic reforms through constitutional correction and
development (Concord).
</P>
<P>
In a weekly radio-TV program here, Estrada said that he is
always ready for talks with Manila Archbishop Cardinal Jaime Sin
and former presidents Corazon Aquino and Fidel Ramos to thrash out
issues involving his administration's call for constitutional
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"We are exploring all possible solutions to our problems.
Perhaps we can talk about this, and I'm ready to talk with former
presidents Aquino and Ramos and Cardinal Sin," he said.
</P>
<P>
Around 75,000 people, led by Cardinal Sin and former president
Aquino, staged an anti-charter-change rally Friday afternoon in
the capital city.
</P>
<P>
In the program, Estrada also appealed to critics of economic
reforms to give his administration a chance to clearly explain to
the people the need to introduce changes to the constitution to
realize his goal of eradicating poverty among Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
"I could have done away with Concord to avoid controversy and
confusion. But, I decided to push through with this because there
is no other solution but to lift the restrictions in the
constitution on the entry of foreign capital," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing constitution, foreigners are not allowed to
own land in the Philippines and their ownership share of the
country's industry can not exceed 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
"That's why I thought of proposing economic reforms to the
constitution and nothing else," he added.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that the move to bring in foreign investments
reflects the new economic nationalism of providing Filipinos with
more jobs and uplifting their living standards.
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms to the constitution will also make the
Philippines at par with its Asian neighbors that have already
forged ahead in the race toward development, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Saturday, the presidential office
said that Estrada's call for economic reforms, which include
allowing foreigners to own land and enter certain businesses and
public utilities, is expected to draw in billions of dollars worth
of investments in real estate and capital-intensive industries.
</P>
