<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization Moves Slowly in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The privatization drive in
Bangladesh has been moving slowly, the Economic Observer reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board invited tenders to off-load some 15
SOEs (state-owned enterprises) between November last year and
August this year, but only two entered into the final stage of
transfer, and the board had to put some SOEs on re-tender.
</P>
<P>
"The privatization goes slow. What can we do if entrepreneurs
do not respond to tenders?" said a board official.
</P>
<P>
The board floated tenders for four enterprise last November,
but could finalize the deal for only one of them. In April this
year, it put five SOEs on sale, and only one of them was in early
stages of selling while there was no response for the four others.
</P>
<P>
Huge long-term and short-term liabilities, separation of land
from factories, procedural delays in handover and excessive
manpower are among the decelerators for the much-needed sell-out,
business people said.
</P>
<P>
"The government lacks strong political decision for quickening
the privatization fearing labor unrest," said an executive member
of the Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and
Industries.
</P>
<P>
Superfluous manpower of the state undertakings frustrate
prospective buyers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Privatization is donors' recipe and the government's top
priority to stop hemorrhage of national exchequer to the tune of
25 billion taka (500 million U.S. dollars) per year on account of
the SOEs.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board, which is now put under the prime
minister's office and has handed over only 18 units so far since
it was set up in 1993, needs government's approval at every stage
to off-load an SOE.
</P>
<P>
"If everything goes smoothly, we need at least six months to
complete the whole journey up to the prime minister's office and
then issue letter of intent for an SOE," said a board official.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the privatization process, the cabinet has approved
a draft law vesting more authority and autonomy upon the board.
The law, if passed in parliament, would empower the board to
directly trade out a state enterprise worth up to 250 million taka
(5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sometimes, it takes one year or more for a buyer to take over
the unit. "In the meantime, the machinery loses capacity and the
entrepreneur loses interest. But we've nothing to help," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 SOEs in the country, with the total value
of output accounting for about 6 percent of the gross domestic
product and incurring a loss of about 568 million dollars every
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0124 </DOCNO>
