<HEADLINE> EU Team to Come to Tanzania to Review Fish Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 21 (Xinhua)-- An European Union
inspection team will arrive here next week to inspect Tanzania's
efforts in controlling toxic fishing in Lake Victoria, a move
which may lead to partial lifting of the ban on fish fillet
exports from the country to Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation's first secretary in Dar es Salaam, Ranieri
Sabatucci, has said a group of veterinarians will be in Tanzania
next Monday to check whether or not Tanzania has made any
improvement in fighting the illegal practices of fishing with
chemical substances that threaten food health.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, EU suspended imports of fresh fish fillets
produced from Lake Victoria, the largest in Africa, following
reports that fishermen of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda have used
cotton pesticides to poison fish. The three countries incurred
great loss in foreign exchange earnings following the trade
embargo.
</P>
<P>
Although the team has already expressed dissatisfaction with
Kenya's failure to enforce required standards, Tanzania might be
considered on an isolated basis, Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, The EU Head of Delegation, Peter Beck
Christiansen, said that Tanzania had fully complied with required
standards and hoped that the ban would be lifted. He however
argued that because Tanzania shares common borders on Lake
Victoria with Uganda and Kenya, it was necessary that the three
countries maintain uniform standard of fish exports.
</P>
<P>
Fish processors say that since imposition of the ban, the price
of fish fillet exports has dropped from 2.5 dollars to between 2.0
dollars and 1.85 dollars per kilogram. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
