<HEADLINE> Tax Dodge Goods Held at Kenyan Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Goods worth more than 50 million
 shillings (around 700,000 U.S. dollars) have been seized by the
customs in a major new crackdown on tax evasion at Mombasa port,
the second largest city in southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
H.P. Ndungu, deputy commissioner of customs at the port, said
that seven Toyota Landcruisers were also being seized, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seized two 40-foot containers and one 20-foot
container following attempts by the clearing agents to evade duty
through false declaration," Ndungu said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the agents had indicated that one of the
containers had 115 cartons of garlic, but after verification, it
was found to contain 115 bales of printed fabrics.
</P>
<P>
The other two containers seized were discovered that the goods
 indicated in the documents submitted to the customs were not the
ones inside the containers, Ndungu added.
</P>
<P>
The goods have been held and the licences of the clearing and
 forwarding agents have been suspended, the customs official said,
adding a manhunt for the directors of clearing and forwarding
companies has been launched.
</P>
<P>
Tax evasion at Mombasa port was on the rise until 1997 when
the government mounted a crackdown on tax evaders. 
</P>
