<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Calls for Suspension of Officials Involved in Bank Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House Commission
VIII (state budget and financial affairs) Saturday issued a
political statement, calling for suspension of state officials
involved in Bank Bali scandal.
</P>
<P>
The political statement was read to reporters by Commission
Chairman Tayo Tarmadi here Saturday morning after a meeting of the
formulating team that lasted for more than five hours.
</P>
<P>
The 13-point political statement should have been drafted by 15
members of the House commission, but two of them, Syaiful Anwar
from the United Development Party faction and Markus Wauran from
the Indonesian Democratic Party faction, were absent.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Bank Bali scandal has shaken
the country's monetary system, weakened the rupiah exchange rate
against the U.S. dollar, and led to the drop of stock trading in
the bourse.
</P>
<P>
Such a condition has been detrimental to the public interest,
lowered international confidence in the Indonesian banking system,
and damaged foundations of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, as a moral and political responsibility, the House
commission called on all state officials and those directly and
indirectly involved in the scandal to be suspended, aimed at
facilitating the investigation of the scandal in line with the
existing laws and regulations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement further said that the minister of finance and the
chairman of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) should
be responsible for the emergence of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
If the Bank Indonesian governor is proven to also be directly
or indirectly involved in the scandal, he should also be
responsible in the framework of public accountability and he
should also be suspended.
</P>
<P>
The House commission demanded that banks unable to meet
recapitalization requirements should also be closed down. In this
connection, the statement called for a review of banks that have
been put under the government-sponsored recapitalization program.
</P>
<P>
The statement also urged the country's legal authorities,
particularly the attorney general's office, to be more pro-active
in probing the Bank Bali scandal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several political parties, including the ruling
Golkar Party, Friday urged Finance Minister Bambang Subianto and
several other officials believed to be implicated in the Bank Bali
scandal to resign.
</P>
<P>
Economist Yusuf Faisal of the National Awakening Party said
that all government officials involved in the Bank Bali case,
including Bambang, IBRA Chairman Glenn Yusuf and Bank Indonesia
Governor Sjahril Sabirin, should resign.
</P>
<P>
"If they do not want to resign, they should appear on
television or place statements in 10 newspapers to apologize,"
Faisal said.
</P>
<P>
The Bank Bali case centered on Bank Bali's transfer early in
June of some 546 billion rupiah (78 million U.S. dollars) to Pt
Era Giat Prima (EGP) as a commission for the company's services in
assisting the bank to recoup some 904 billion rupiah (129 million
dollars) in interbank claims on closed Bank Dagang Nasional
Indonesia (BDNI).
</P>
<P>
Part of the money allegedly went to finance the money politics
activities of the so-call "(President B.J.) Habibie Success Team"
which aims to secure the "re-election" of the incumbent president,
who is Golkar's presidential candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
