<HEADLINE> PAL, Lufthansa to Discuss Maintenance Unit Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' flag carrier
Philippine Airlines (PAL) and German carrier Lufthansa Technik Ag
will hold formal talks next month on the impending sale of the
PAL's maintenance and engineering (M&AMP;E) unit based in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa is expected to wrap up its due diligence study of the
M&AMP;E operations in September so the formal negotiation can begin,
the Philippine News Agency said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that PAL President and Chief Operating Officer
Avelino Zapanta has confirmed the upcoming talks but refused to
discuss any details.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa has engaged the services of Asian Appraisals to
undertake the critical inventory of the M&AMP;E property equipment,
and Price Waterhouse to conduct an audit of the total business
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency said, problems may crop up because of a
possible disagreement between joint-venture partners Lufthansa
and airport services firm MacroAsia Corp.
</P>
<P>
Even before Lufthansa's due diligence audit began, industry
officials said the German aircraft maintenance firm expressed its
intention to hold the majority stake in the new joint-venture
company.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, MacroAsia management had also informed
PAL that it, too, wanted majority ownership.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, a PAL official said the company is more inclined
to a "50-50" arrangement.
</P>
<P>
He added that PAL will try to get the best terms possible and
make the negotiations "very transparent" so as not to get any
complaints from its creditors, to whom the PAL owes 2.2 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
