<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Harsh Economic Climate Hits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The current harsh macro-economic
climate in Zimbabwe has hit the country's agricultural production
because of farmers' weak resource base, Minister of Lands and
Agriculture Kumbirai Kangai Friday said at the close of the
two-day Zimbabwe Farmers' Union 60th congress in south Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said the country had in the last two years experienced a
very harsh economic environment that impacted negatively on
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
"This harsh macro-economic climate is still with us and
preparations for the 1999/2000 production season are being made
under very difficult conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the harsh economic conditions would make it
difficult for farmers to invest in agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Despite these difficulties, agriculture remains the most
critical sector to the economic growth and development of the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture has made a significant contribution to the
country's economic development and continues to play a central
role in employment, export earnings, provision of food and supply
of raw materials to the manufacturing sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will continue to play this major role in creating a stable
macro- economic climate through increased crop and livestock
production. To have a sustainable economic growth, Zimbabwe needs
a dynamic agricultural sector, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said there was no doubt that the potential for growth of
the agricultural sector was largely in the small holder sector.
</P>
<P>
"The small holder sector has a lot of underutilized labor
which, if given the opportunity and the necessary resources, can
revive and drive the growth of the agricultural sector," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
