<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Discovers Terra Cotta Horses From Western Zhou Dynasty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The recently discovered terra
cotta horses and carriages from the Jin Kingdom in Quwo County,
north China's Shanxi Province, has proved to be 600 years earlier
than those in Xi'an, northwest China's Shaanxi, which were made in
the Qin Dynasty (221 B.C.-207 B.C.), said archeologists after
investigation and study.
</P>
<P>
Overall excavation of the relics has begun recently. And up to
now six horse-carriage pits have been unearthed, with over 100
horses and more than 50 carriages discovered. The pits,
constructed during the Western Zhou Dynasty (11th Century B.C.-
771 B.C.), have been the largest and most complete.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that the unearthed daily-use carriages and
chariots with various designs and of different sizes, demonstrate
the extraordinary political, economic and military strength of the
Jin Kingdom as one of the five strongest kingdoms at that time.
</P>
<P>
And they believed that the discovery will be of great help in
the study of the dynasty's politics, economic conditions and
military affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
