<HEADLINE> UAE Plans to Market Dates in U.S., Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Plans are well under way in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) to market dates, one of the major
agricultural products in the desert country, in the United States
and European countries.
</P>
<P>
The output of dates this year can meet the domestic market need
and a surplus will go for processing and export to international
markets, the Khaleej Times daily reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The dates harvest season is very promising this year and we
are looking forward to entering international markets including
the United States and some European countries," said Mohammed
Suhail Al Mazroui, director of Abu Dahbi-based Mirfa Dates and
Vegetables Processing and Packing Factory.
</P>
<P>
He said marketing centers in the country had received large
quantities of dates and many more would come in the next few
days. Initial agreements and contracts to market this season's
harvest locally and internationally have been signed, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a marketing and processing plan has been
drafted by the factory which has been expanded and equipped with
hi-tech machinery. The overall production standards and the
industrial quality of the factory are now very high.
</P>
<P>
"This development has brought forth further ambitious plans to
develop local industries and replace food imports with local
products and to further export the surplus," Mazroui said.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural exports from the UAE - mainly vegetables - have
been declining recently, largely because of an increased demand
from a growing population and a consequent small surplus
availability, according to the Khaleej Times report.
</P>
<P>
Date palm trees occupy almost 50 percent of the total
cultivated area in the country, with the rest being planted with
vegetables, fruits and other crops. Dates export, however, is
very small. 
</P>
</TEXT>
