<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Developments in China's Basic Science Research (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The People's Republic of China
has made many achievements in the fields of basic science and high
technology research since it was founded in 1949. The achievements,
which are of the world's advanced level, have greatly promoted the
economic development and scientific progress.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, the Chinese Academy of Sciences started research
in space science and technology, and has provided thousands of
high quality components and parts and new materials  with special
functions for China-made satellites, radar, remote control and
monitoring systems, and telecommunication systems.
</P>
<P>
In the middle of the 1960s, China successfully developed atomic
and hydrogen bombs. In 1970, China launched its first man-made
satellite, which provided a technological basis for future
development on satellite communication and meteorological service.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of reform and opening-up policies in
1978, China has improved its basic research and knowledge
innovation capacity by establishing a national natural science
foundation, launching major scientific projects and building state
key laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The National Committee of the Natural Science Foundation, which
was founded in 1986, has been receiving money from the government
budget each year for the basic research fund. The fund, increasing
on a year-to-year basis, stood at 780 million yuan (about 94
million US dollars) in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Developments of China's Basic Science Research (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past two decades, China has spent 720 million yuan (
about 87 million US dollars) on 11 major research projects of high-
energy physics, nuclear physics, synchrotron radiation and nuclear
fusion. They include the heavy ion accelerator, the electron
positron collidor, the synchrotron radiation accelerator and the 2.
16-meter optical astronomical telescope which are developed by the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS). Since 1985, the CAS has founded
more than 100 national key laboratories which are open to Chinese
and foreign research organizations, and has provided them with
advanced scientific facilities.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period, China has launched the
second phase of the national synchrotron radiation laboratory,
built up the Chinese earth crest monitoring system, the Large Sky
Area Multi-Object Fiber Spectroscopy Telescope (LAMOST) and the HT-
7U Tok Mark fusion device.
</P>
<P>
During the period, basic research in China has made big
progress, with many scientific findings with the high temperature
superconductor, the mechanization of mathematics, the physical
patterns of the paddle's genome and animal fossils in Chengjiang,
south China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China is implementing the Development Program of
National Key Basic Research Projects. According to the program,
China will provide funds in the next decade to research on major
scientific problems in agriculture, energy, information, resource
and environment, population and health, material and other fields.
</P>
<P>
The first group of 15 basic research projects have already been
launched with a total investment of 170 million yuan (about 20
million US dollars) in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
