<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Trade Union Slams New Salaries for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) has condemned the182-percent salary hike for
government ministers, describing the increase as "outrageous" and
"totally unacceptable", the daily Herald reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement last night, the ZCTU Secretary-General Morgan
Tsvangirai said it was cheap politicking to compare Zimbabwe with
other countries in the region instead of considering the serious
economic crisis the country was facing.
</P>
<P>
"Dust has barely settled when civil servants were pleading for
a mere 20- percent cost of living adjustment which was met with
fierce resistance by the powers that be," Tsvangirai said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The labor movement totally condemns this appalling
insensitivity and, in the light of this shocking development, the
ZCTU will immediately engage in consultations with civil servants
and the rest of its affiliates."
</P>
<P>
The August 19 issue of The Financial Gazette reported that
government ministers had been awarded a 182-percent salary
increment backdated to July.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information, Posts and Telecommunications Chen
Chimutengwende was quoted in the local Press defending the
increases, saying Zimbabwe's Cabinet ministers were the lowest
paid in the Southern African Development Community (SADC) region.
</P>
