<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Slum Dwellers Occupy Supreme Court Premises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of evicted slum dwellers
who entered the Supreme Court premises in central Dhaka Wednesday
night have built makeshift homes there like their demolished
shanties.
</P>
<P>
The slum people refused to leave the area until their demand of
immediate rehabilitation was met, press reports here said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 squatters, who camped in Osmany Uddyan, a park near
the Secretariat housing government ministries and agencies,
following their eviction from slums earlier this month, moved to
the court premises Wednesday evening and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The occupation of the court premises by the squatters
"embarrassed" the High Court Bench which was hearing the case of
the slum dwellers Thursday and earlier passed a stay order on
eviction until the next date of hearing.
</P>
<P>
The court bench adjourned its hearing following the
"unprecedented" move in the court area, and referred the writ
petition, filed by some non-government organizations and slum
dwellers challenging the evictions, to the Chief Justice who later
passed the matter to another bench. The hearing was adjourned till
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I've heard that the court is very sympathetic to us and I've
been asked by some other people to come here," a slum dweller was
quoted by The Independent daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Bangladesh Bastuhara Samity (BBS), an
organization for the poor homeless people, were seen organizing
the slum dwellers on the court premises, the report said. Munshi
Mohammad Ali, treasurer of the BBS, said they had come to the
Supreme Court compound following a decision by the organization.
</P>
<P>
The BBS, reportedly a front organization of the ruling
Bangladesh Awami League (BAL), has the same official address as
the BAL, The New Nation newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Thursday police turned down a request for removing the poor
people swarming in the court premises.
</P>
<P>
"We need a written order from the court, otherwise we feel it
would be in violation of the court orders to purge the former slum
people," a police official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government mounted a four-day drive to evict the slum
dwellers in the capital city earlier this month saying that the
slums had become dens of terrorists and criminals. Nearly 70,000
people were evicted from slums.
</P>
<P>
It is said there are about 2 million slum dwellers in the
Bangladeshi capital, home for some 9 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
