<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Closes 18 Ports Threatened by Storm "Bret" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Mexican authorities Friday
closed 18 ports along the Gulf of Mexico to small and medium craft
navigation as the tropical storm "Bret" could strengthen into a
hurricane and hit the country's eastern coasts.
</P>
<P>
Storm Bret, carrying sustained winds at 102 kilometers per hour,
continues moving to the north of the Gulf, according to a
communique of the Communications and Transports Ministry (SCT).
</P>
<P>
The SCT said that four of the 18 ports closed are in the state
of Tamaulipas, nine in Veracruz, and five in Tabasco.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon, Bret was located 293 kilometers east of
the Gulf port city of Tuxpan in the state of Veracruz, and 375
kilometers southeast of port Tampico in Tamaulipas. It had a
radius of 165 kilometers, and was moving northwards about 10
kilometers with maximum sustained winds nearing 100 kilometers per
hour.
</P>
<P>
The Civil protection authorities were on alert in the port city
of Tampico, 350 kilometers northeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
A hurricane warning had once been extended to as far north as
the coastal town of La Pesca, 550 kilometers north of the port
city of Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
According to the United States National Hurricane Center in
Miami, tropical storm Bret could strengthen into a hurricane by
Friday night or Saturday, and reach Mexico's eastern coasts
probably on Monday anywhere from La Pesca to Veracruz, where a
hurricane watch is in effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
