<HEADLINE> DPRK Condemns Japan-U.S. Deal on Anti-Missile System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Japan-U.S. deal on an anti-
missile system, known as the Theater Missile Defense (TMD),
undermines peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region, said
the official Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
"Such grave developments disturbing peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region are arousing deep apprehension and high
vigilance from among the regional people," the KCNA said in a
comment issued on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese cabinet approved the TMD plan on August 13 and
signed a formal agreement and memorandum of understanding with the
United States on Monday to jointly research the anti-ballistic
missile system.
</P>
<P>
Japan has claimed that its decision to join the TMD is out of
concerns over "missile threats" from the DPRK, alleging that a man-
made satellite launched by Pyongyang on August 31 last year was a
medium-range missile.
</P>
<P>
Since June this year, the United States and Japan had sped up
their talks on the TMD on the ground that the DPRK might be
preparing to test-fire another upgraded ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
"As known to everyone, the TMD system is a system of reinvasion
to make preemptive attack and contain the DPRK and a war system to
prevail over big powers in the Asia-Pacific region," the KCNA said.
</P>
<P>
The comment said Japan's "reckless military threat" could not
work in the DPRK, as the "launch of satellite or missile is a
matter pertaining to our sovereignty" and "we will exercise this
sovereignty unhesitatingly at our own will, if necessary."
</P>
</TEXT>
