<HEADLINE> Ecuador Asks IMF to Cancel Interests Payment on Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador has proposed to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to cancel the payment of
interests on its Brady bonds that falls due August 31, Finance
Minister Ana Lucia Armijos said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador had dismissed until a few weeks ago the possibility of
a cancellation of interests payment on the bonds, which would
amount to 94 million U.S. dollars by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Ecuadorian President Jamil Mahuad said his country
was seeking "market" solutions to restructure its huge debt, and
announced that an IMF mission will arrive Saturday in Quito to
close a possible deal.
</P>
<P>
If Ecuador cancels the payment, it will be the first country to
do it, and the market would be seriously affected, said
international analysts.
</P>
<P>
The Brady bonds were named after former U.S. Secretary of the
Treasury Nicholas Brady. Structured more than a decade ago, they
are instruments of commercial debt that foresees a reduction of
the debt or of the interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
