<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Urged to Fire Top Finance Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian ruling Golkar Party
Friday urged that President B.J. Habibie dismiss Minister of
Finance Bambang Subianto and Chairman of the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency (IBRA) Glenn S. Yusuf over the Bank Bali
scandal.
</P>
<P>
Golkar legislator Thomas Suyatno said "responsibility for
policy mistakes must be taken by policy decision-makers, which in
this case are the Ministry of Finance and the chairman of IBRA".
</P>
<P>
"(We demand) that firm measures be taken against all government
officials as well as officials from other institutions who are
directly or indirectly involved (in the case)... in the form of
dismissing them to allow a thorough investigation," he was quoted
Saturday by The Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Following Thursday's hearing session on the Bank Bali affair
with the government and Bank Indonesia, the Golkar faction at the
House of Representatives released a 13-point statement calling for
Bambang and Glen to tender their resignations.
</P>
<P>
Thomas also said that if Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril
Sabirin was found in the future to be directly or indirectly
involved in the affair, he would also have to resign.
</P>
<P>
The United Development Party faction has urged Bambang and
Glenn resign, or be temporarily suspended, until investigation of
the matter is completed.
</P>
<P>
During Thursday's hearing session, which ran from 10 a.m. until
10 p.m. local time, most of the commission VIII legislators were
apparently pushing Bambang and Glenn to acknowledge that a mistake
had been made. But Bambang and Glenn maintained that payment of
Bank Bali's interbank claims had followed established procedures.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary/Justice Minister Muladi Friday denied reports
that Habibie had considered dismissing Bambang and Glenn.
</P>
<P>
"We'll watch the developments. The House has not yet (had its
final say)," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to The Indonesian Observer, the House is expected to
summon Habibie to provide an explanation on the bank scam.
</P>
<P>
The Bank Bali case, first revealed to the media late July,
centered on Bank Bali's transfer in early June of some 546 billion
rupiah (78 million U.S. dollars) to PT Era Giat Prima (EGP) as a
commission for the firm's "service" in assisting the bank to
recoup some 904 billion rupiah in interbank claims on closed-down
Bank Dagang Nasional Indonesia (BDNI).
</P>
<P>
EGP is a company owned by businessmen Djoko Chandra and Setya
Novanto, both of whom are affiliated to the Golkar. Most of the
commission allegedly landed in the hands of Habibie's close
associates in charge of leading the team to secure his election in
the November presidential election.
</P>
<P>
A document containing the transcript of confessions made by
former Bank Bali president Rudy Ramli on the involvement of
cabinet ministers, senior government officials and business
tycoons in the scandal was circulated among legislators on August
19.
</P>
<P>
Election winner Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle said it
has hard evidence showing the direct involvement of 16 people in
the scam.
</P>
<P>
The National Mandate Party Friday urged the House to thoroughly
investigate the Bank Bali case, as it believed the scandal
involved powerful people close to the president.
</P>
<P>
The party said there were indications of efforts to scapegoat
individuals, with key players left untouched.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Police General Roesmanhadi Friday reiterated that the
police will continue its investigation of the Bank Bali scandal,
and a number of high-ranking officials will soon be summoned for
interrogation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
