<HEADLINE> Central America Discusses Security Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Central American officials
gathered here Friday for a one-day meeting on security problems in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Judicial and Political Affairs Counselor to the Central
American Integration System, Mauricio Herdocia, told Xinhua that
the center theme of the meeting is the Basic Treaty of Democratic
Security.
</P>
<P>
Crime has now become an international issue, and coordinated
action is demanded to combat it, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-foreign ministers and vice-interior ministers from Costa
Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Panama
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Costa Rican Vice-Foreign Minister
Walter Niehaus highlighted the importance of monitoring migration
problems and conditions in border ports, which are needed to speed
up trade and prevent illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Delegates discussed proposals to establish a reasonable balance
of power between the countries of the Isthmus, to heighten
security, and to make security forces more transparent by more
clearly defining their role and activities, and to invite
observers from all nations in the area to observe military
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
Participants are also concerned about security in case of
natural disasters, especially after the devastation left last year
by hurricane "Mitch" which seriously affected Nicaragua and
Honduras, said Niehaus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
