<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Central Bank's Bonds Auction Pulls Dollar Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar dropped 1.18
percent in Brazil Friday, with the purchase price of the real, the
national currency, closing at 1.91, and the selling price at 1.92,
following an auction of Central Bank (BC) bonds.
</P>
<P>
The dollar opened bullish Friday and rose to 1.98 buying and 1.
99 selling. The auction of 3 billion reals (1.56 billion dollars)
of the BC, however, pushed back the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar ended the week in the Sao Paulo parallel market with
a quote of 1.97 reals to buy and 2.01 to sell.
</P>
<P>
Before the auction, the Brazilian real skidded to a five-month
low on Friday, pushed by uncertainty about deficit-cutting reforms
and flagging investor confidence in South American markets.
</P>
<P>
For Brazilians, the scramble to buy dollars was uncomfortably
reminiscent of the panic that followed the 1997 crisis in
southeast Asia and last year's turmoil in Russia. Shock waves
eventually reached Brazil, which was forced to devalue its
currency in January and plunged into a recession from which it is
now emerging.
</P>
<P>
Authorities were quick to argue that the situation now is very
different.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank President Arminio Fraga said markets had the wrong
impression the government was weakening in its resolve to enact
deficit-cutting reforms, a condition required by the International
Monetary Fund for a 41.5 billion-dollar loan last year.
</P>
<P>
"The market is nervous now," Amalia Estensorro, a Latin
American economist at BBV Latinvest in London said this week. "
International currencies are a bit wobbly in general, but
particularly in Brazil, because of the uncertainty of the fiscal
situation."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
