<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economists Urge Govt to Improve Its Credibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of Indonesian noted
economists issued an "Economic Memorandum" aiming to improve the
credibility of the current government of President B.J. Habibie,
national newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the five-point declaration, they noted that under the
present government, various economic scandals had occurred in the
country, such as corruption in the distribution of social safety
net program funds, concessional credits and bank closure scandals.
</P>
<P>
Other cases were the bank recapitalization program and the
implementation of the government's program to guarantee liquidated
banks' liabilities which led to the Bank Bali scandal that had
inflicted enormous damage on the entire bank restructuring
program.
</P>
<P>
"A credible government is a must. In many cases, no matter how
good an economic policy is, it won't work if the ruling government
has no credibility," said Sri Mulyani Indrawati, the group's
spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
In their memorandum, the economists said that to improve its
credibility, the government must take concrete steps as a
reference for running the country's administration and economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
The government should also act to ensure that its policies and
economic recovery move in the right direction, remain consistent
and transparent, and eliminate potential weaknesses in the
implementation of its policies, while at all times managing the
economy based on the principle of prudence in stabilization
efforts.
</P>
<P>
It said the government is and will be facing a very heavy
fiscal burden due to, among others, bank restructuring costs and
debt repayments -- both principal and interest.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to stimulate the economy can be conducted through the
empowerment of the private sector and the (financial) markets, as
well as through the opening of investment opportunities," it said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum is the result of a two-day conference titled
"The Economic Issues Facing the New Government.".
</P>
<P>
Signatories to the memorandum include Marie Pangestu from the
Center for Strategic and International Studies, Anggito Abimanyu
from Gadjah Mada University and M. Chatib Basri from the
University of Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
