<HEADLINE> Chile, Argentina to Promote Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chile and Argentina signed a
series of accords on Friday to promote bilateral cooperation and
subregional integration.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, signed here during the official visit by
Argentine President Carlos Menem, committed the two countries to
joint efforts in fighting drug trafficking and money laundering,
and in the joint production of naval vessels.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on scientific and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement signed by President Menem and Chilean
President Eduardo Frei, they vowed to liberalize commercial air
traffic between their two countries. They agreed to convene a
meeting between relevant parties before September 30.
</P>
<P>
Frei stated Chile's support for Argentina in its territorial
dispute with Britain over the Malvinas Islands; he also appealed
for a prompt solution to the dispute in line with United Nations
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents expressed satisfaction at the level of
cooperation and dialogue between the armed forces of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
President Menem was here after launching on Thursday with Frei
a natural gas pipeline which is considered important to the
economic development of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The joint pipeline project marked an end to nearly two decades
of mistrust and frozen political and economic ties between Chile
and Argentina, once on the brink of war over three islands located
at the southern tip of South America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
