<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRRI Comes up with Iron-and-Zinc-Rich Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines-based
International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) has developed an
iron-and-zinc-rich rice, which is expected to dramatically improve
the diet of women, infants and toddlers.
</P>
<P>
The Malaya newspaper Saturday quoted IRRI project scientist
Glenn Gregorio as saying that the rice variety could cure
nutritional anemia, or "hidden hunger" in children and women.
</P>
<P>
Gregorio said that IRRI scientists developed the
iron-and-zinc-rich rice after years of research.
</P>
<P>
Nutritional anemia -- caused by low dietary intake and
bio-availability of iron, blood loss due to parasites, and
unsatisfied demand associated with rapid growth and pregnancy --
limits learning capacity during childhood, impairs immune function
and reduces labor productivity.
</P>
<P>
A World Health Organization survey shows that 3.7 billion
people in the world are iron-deficient, severe enough to cause
anemia in 2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
Gregorio said that efforts to combat malnutrition by
artificially fortifying milled rice has encouraged them to develop
improved germ plasma with enhanced iron and zinc in the grain.
</P>
<P>
Doubling or tripling iron or zinc contents in rice could
improve the health of those at risk, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
