<DOCNO> XIE19990821.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Affirms Blood Tests for Sydney Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, Spain, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Some form of blood
testing will be introduced at next year's Sydney Olympics in the
wake of spate of high-profile drug scandals in athletics and other
sports.
</P>
<P>
In another move to step up the fight against drugs, the
International Olympic Committee determined that a world anti-
doping agency will be set up by the end of this year and will be
operational for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
The drug issue was mainly discussed in an IOC executive board
meeting on the eve of the World Athletics Championships opening
Saturday here because several performance-enhancing drugs, such as
human growth hormone and EPO (erythropoietin), can not be detected
in current standard urine tests.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to have a blood test that could be used as part of
the official doping control procedures during the Sydney Games.
The blood tests could also be implemented in out-of-competition
controls on the eve of the Sydney Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
