</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain signaled Friday that it would not expel the
IRA's political wing from a planned review of Northern Ireland's
stalled peace accord even if it decides that the guerrilla group
has broken its two-year-old ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam hinted that any breach
might be penalized by suspension of a scheme for early release of
jailed IRA members. (Britain-Sinn Fein)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Uganda and Rwanda, best allies in the region but
supporting different factions of the main rebel group in the Congo,
turned guns against each other in Kisangani in northeastern Congo
recently, overshadowing the fragile peace process aimed at
resolving the year-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
The clashes, which reportedly erupted on Saturday and lasted
till Tuesday, was for the control of an airport in Kisangani where
Ugandan troops were greatly outnumbered and out gunned. Dozens of
soldiers died in the exchange of gunfire. (Uganda-Rwanda-Clashes)
</P>
