<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Returns to F1 Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Emotions were running high at the
Mugello circuit in Italy's Scarperia, near central city of
Florence Friday as Ferrari's injured driving ace Michael
Schumacher made a stunning return to the track, beating his
teammate Eddie Irvine's best time in the previous day.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian news agency Ansa, Schumacher, shortly
after his helicopter landed on the track, slipped into his Formula
1 car and clocked a lap in 1.28.732, bettering Irvine's best time
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
After lunch, he improved on his time by clocking in at 1.28.72,
and shortly afterwards raced a lap in 1.28.70, this time shedding
a fraction of a second off his substitute, Mika Salo's best time
in Thursday's practice runs.
</P>
<P>
Marking his return after an accident forty days ago that left
him with a broken leg, the double world champion got a hero's
welcome from his team of mechanics, and even received the visit of
Umberto Agnelli, brother of Fiat's honor boss Gianni Agnelli, who
watched several of his test runs.
</P>
<P>
"I was happy about the team's welcome, and it was nice to see
my friends again," Umberto said, adding "It was like coming home
after too long a holiday."
</P>
<P>
Schumacher's doctor was also on hand, to check that "no
problems surfaced," according to the Ferrari team's spokesman,
Claudio Berro, who added that "everything is going to plan."
</P>
<P>
But, in spite of his surprising performance Friday, the
consequences of Schumacher's accident were still evident as he
limped round the paddock.
</P>
<P>
Chances of his return at next week's Belgian Grand Prix at Spa,
on August 29, remained limited; a return at the Italian Grand Prix
at Monza, on September 12, is seen as a virtual certainty.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher was visibly raring to drive, after doctors Thursrday
gave him the green light to get back behind the wheel of a Formula
1 car.
</P>
<P>
"I'll see how fit I am in the next few days, and after another
medical check-up, I'll decide with the team whether I can come
back at Monza or before," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
