<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seville Opens World Championships with 2008 Olympics on Its Mind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, Spain, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Filling the Olympic
stadium that was completed three months ago, some 2,000 athletes
from a record 204 countries and regions joined on Friday for the
World Athletics Championships opening ceremony -- a spectacle
intended to show the history and future of the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
"A few years ago it seemed like a dream and now, as of today,
it has come true," said Calos Herrera, mayor of Seville.
</P>
<P>
The mayor added: "They say that Seville '99 is the last great
sports event of the 20th century. I prefer to think that these
World Championships in Seville will be the first of the new
Millennium."
</P>
<P>
The World Championships, which will run until August 29, was
regarded as the third sports gala in the world, only next to the
Olympic Games and the World Cup football tournament.
</P>
<P>
Athletes entered the stadium behind the flags of their nations -
-the most ever at a major international sporting competition,
organizers said. The colors of the flags were in sharp contrast to
the white cloth which covered the seats of the guests, athletes
and coaches on the field.
</P>
<P>
Primo Nebiolo, head of the International Amateur Athletics
Federation, spoke high of Seville's efforts in preparing for the
championships.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Seville unites 204 countries and regions from around
the world. Your dreams, your sacrifices, your hard work and
dedication have made it possible to welcome more athletes here
than in any previous single athletics event ever."
</P>
<P>
After the IAAF's flag appears carried by athletes and is
hoisted to the top of the stadium, his Royal Highness Prince
Felipe of Borbon declared the World Championships open.
</P>
<P>
The world championships was also part of Seville's efforts to
bid for the 2008 summer Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
But the Spanish city, which lost the bidding campaign for the
2004 Games, faces fierce challenge from other candidates including
Beijing, Istanbul, Toronto, Paris and Osaka with Beijing
considered the favorite. At least four other cities are weighing a
bid.
</P>
<P>
Seville also hosted the Expo '92 universal fair -- one of the
highlights of Spain's 500th anniversary celebration of Columbus'
journey to America.
</P>
<P>
The competition will start on Saturday with three gold medals
to be decided in the women's pole vault, men's 20 kilometers walk
and men's shot put. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
