<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Bounce Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rebounded
Friday ahead of the expected rise in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 136.77 at 11,100.61.
The blue chip index fell 153.24 points in the two previous
sessions but still gained 126.96 points for the week.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 13.02 at 1,336.61 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 26.90 at 2,648.33.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied as investors bought some stocks, seeking
safe bets in case interest rates continue to rise. The Federal
Reserve is expected to raise interest rates by a
quarter-percentage point next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve raised the short-term rates by 0.25 percent
to 5.0 percent on June 30.
</P>
<P>
The market was also helped to move higher by strong U.S. dollar
that steadied against foreign currencies today after Thursday's
dropping to its lowest level against the Japanese yen since
January. The weak dollar dragged stocks lower in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 5.73 at 626.09 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.72 at 787.79. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.61 at 434.38.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,734 up, 1,226 down and 565
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 658.10 million shares from 673.68
million in the previous session. 
</P>
